    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Gagea subalpina are infusion, tincture, tea, salve, and decoction. Infusion involves steeping the flowers in hot water to produce a liquid extract, while tincture involves soaking the plant material in a solvent, typically ethanol or glycerol, to create a concentrated liquid extract. Tea is prepared by infusing the flowers in hot water, similar to infusion, but often in a larger quantity and for a shorter time. A salve is a topical preparation made by infusing the flowers in a carrier oil, such as olive or coconut oil, to create a medicinal ointment. Decoction involves boiling the flowers in water, often for a longer period, to extract the more soluble compounds, such as alkaloids and glycosides.",
